2 HOUSE BILL 297
1 Annotated Code of Maryland
2 (2025 Replacement Volume)
3 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
4 Article – Labor and Employment
5 Section 11–808(b)
6 Annotated Code of Maryland
7 (2025 Replacement Volume)
8 BY adding to
9 Article – Labor and Employment
10 Section 11–808.1 and 11–810
11 Annotated Code of Maryland
12 (2025 Replacement Volume)
13 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
14 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
15 Article – Labor and Employment
16 11–808.
17 (a) An individual may obtain a high school diploma by examination as provided
18 in this section if the individual:
19 (1) has not obtained a high school diploma;
20 (2) resides in this State; and
21 (3) except as provided in subsection (b) of this section:
22 (i) is not subject to compulsory school attendance under § 7–301 of
23 the Education Article; and
24 (ii) has withdrawn from a regular full–time public or private school
25 program.
26 (b) An individual is not subject to the requirements of subsection (a)(3) of this
27 section if the individual participates in:
28 (1) a GED Option Program administered by the State Department of
29 Education that creates a pathway to a high school diploma by examination for currently
30 enrolled high school English language learner students under the age of 21 years who have
31 experienced interrupted education and have a lower level of English proficiency than their
32 peers; OR

HOUSE BILL 297 3
1 (2) THE GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER §
2 11–808.1 OF THIS SUBTITLE.
3 11–808.1.
4 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “PILOT PROGRAM” MEANS THE GED OPTION PILOT
5 PROGRAM.
6 (B) (1) THERE IS A GED OPTION PILOT PROGRAM IN THE STATE.
7 (2) THE PURPOSE OF THE PILOT PROGRAM IS TO EXPAND THE GED
8 OPTION PROGRAM TO STUDENTS BEYOND ENGLISH LANGUAGE LEARNERS IN
9 SELECTED SCHOOL DISTRICTS TO ENSURE THAT THE STUDENTS HAVE A PATHWAY
10 TO OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA AND ARE PREPARED TO ENTER
11 POSTSECONDARY PROGRAMMING OR THE WORKFORCE.
12 (C) THE PILOT PROGRAM SHALL BEGIN IN THE 2027–2028 SCHOOL YEAR
13 AND SHALL CONTINUE FOR 2 SCHOOL YEARS.
14 (D) THE DEPARTMENT:
15 (1) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
16 EDUCATION AND THE PUBLIC SCHOOL SUPERINTENDENTS’ ASSOCIATION OF
17 MARYLAND, SHALL DEVELOP CRITERIA, INCLUDING RECOGNITION OF GEOGRAPHIC
18 DIVERSITY, FOR THE SELECTION OF AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO
19 PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
20 (2) IN CONSULTATION WITH THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF
21 EDUCATION, SHALL USE THE CRITERIA DEVELOPED UNDER ITEM (1) OF THIS
22 SUBSECTION TO SELECT AT LEAST THREE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS TO PARTICIPATE
23 IN THE PILOT PROGRAM.
24 (E) EACH COUNTY SUPERINTENDENT FROM A PARTICIPATING LOCAL
25 SCHOOL SYSTEM MAY SELECT UP TO 150 STUDENTS TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT
26 PROGRAM.
27 (F) A STUDENT SELECTED TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PILOT PROGRAM:
28 (1) MAY BEGIN THE GED OPTION PROGRAM WHEN THE STUDENT IS
29 AT LEAST 17 YEARS OLD;
30 (2) MUST BE AT SIGNIFICANT RISK OF NOT SUCCESSFULLY
31 COMPLETING HIGH SCHOOL; AND

4 HOUSE BILL 297
1 (3) SHALL TAKE THE HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY EXAMINATION
2 BEFORE THE CONCLUSION OF THE GED OPTION PROGRAM.
3 (G) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
4 SHALL EXPLORE OPTIONS FOR EXPANDING THE GED OPTION PROGRAM BASED ON
5 RESULTS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.
6 (H) (1) ON OR BEFORE DECEMBER 1, 2028, AND DECEMBER 1, 2029, THE
7 DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION JOINTLY SHALL
8 REPORT TO THE GOVERNOR AND, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
9 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY REGARDING THE
10 EFFECTIVENESS OF THE PILOT PROGRAM.
11 (2) THE REPORT REQUIRED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
12 SUBSECTION SHALL INCLUDE:
13 (I) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT
14 PROGRAM FROM EACH PARTICIPATING LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEM;
15 (II) FEEDBACK FROM EDUCATORS, STUDENTS, AND PARENTS OF
16 STUDENTS PARTICIPATING IN THE PILOT PROGRAM ON WAYS TO IMPROVE THE
17 GED OPTION PROGRAM;
18 (III) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS WHO EARNED A HIGH SCHOOL
19 DIPLOMA AS A RESULT OF COMPLETING THE PILOT PROGRAM; AND
20 (IV) AN EVALUATION OF THE PILOT PROGRAM AND THE GED
21 OPTION PROGRAM WITH ANY RECOMMENDATIONS FOR IMPROVEMENTS.
22 (I) THE DEPARTMENT AND THE STATE DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION
23 JOINTLY MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS TO IMPLEMENT THE PILOT PROGRAM.
24 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Laws of Maryland read
25 as follows:
26 Article – Labor and Employment
27 11–810.
28 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY” MEANS AN
29 ALTERNATIVE PATHWAY TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA IN THE STATE.

HOUSE BILL 297 5
1 (B) THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IS A METHOD TO RECOGNIZE AND
2 CERTIFY HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA ACHIEVEMENT THROUGH DEMONSTRATED
3 ACADEMIC AND CAREER COMPETENCIES, INCLUDING WORKFORCE EXPERIENCE.
4 (C) AN INDIVIDUAL MAY OBTAIN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE
5 MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IF THE INDIVIDUAL:
6 (1) HAS NOT OBTAINED A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA;
7 (2) RESIDES IN THE STATE;
8 (3) IS NOT SUBJECT TO THE COMPULSORY SCHOOL ATTENDANCE
9 REQUIREMENT UNDER § 7–301 OF THE EDUCATION ARTICLE; AND
10 (4) HAS WITHDRAWN FROM A REGULAR FULL–TIME PUBLIC OR
11 PRIVATE SCHOOL PROGRAM.
12 (D) TO EARN A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA THROUGH THE MDIPLOMAWORKS
13 PATHWAY, AN INDIVIDUAL SHALL DEMONSTRATE EQUIVALENCY TO A MARYLAND
14 HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA BY COMPLETION OF A COMBINATION OF THE FOLLOWING
15 COMPONENTS AS APPROVED BY THE DEPARTMENT:
16 (1) EARNING INDUSTRY–RECOGNIZED CREDENTIALS;
17 (2) DEMONSTRATING FOUNDATIONAL ACADEMIC SKILLS THROUGH
18 FORMAL ASSESSMENTS;
19 (3) COMPLETING CAREER AND TECHNICAL EDUCATION
20 COURSEWORK; AND
21 (4) COMPLETING AN ON–THE–JOB LEARNING EXPERIENCE.
22 (E) A HIGH SCHOOL DIPLOMA SHALL BE AWARDED TO AN INDIVIDUAL WHO
23 COMPLETES THE MDIPLOMAWORKS PATHWAY IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE
24 REGULATIONS ADOPTED BY THE SECRETARY AND THE STATE BOARD OF
25 EDUCATION.
26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, in calendar years 2027 and
27 2028, the Maryland Department of Labor shall publish on its website, and include in any
28 publications that describe how adults may obtain a high school diploma, information on the
29 MDiplomaWorks pathway established under § 11–810 of the Labor and Employment
30 Article, as enacted by Section 1 of this Act, in order to inform potentially eligible applicants
31 about the new pathway to obtain a high school diploma.

6 HOUSE BILL 297
1 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
2 October 1, 2026. Section 1 of this Act shall remain effective for a period of 4 years and, at
3 the end of September 30, 2030, Section 1 of this Act, with no further action required by the
4 General Assembly, shall be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
